{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":533,"record_hash":"sha256:d585b09ad566e95f0f6b8c13d3feac3e88036aeb80e437ec6f0e64d93e9c8902","timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:14:21.849Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: fd9e8e\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3304\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of a\ncapture turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A capture turn layer would preserve that missing context without\nforcing us to immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit,\nchange, or pull request.\n\n## V1 Contract\n\nImplement v1 around persisted capture observations, derived indexes, and\nread-time association. Do not persist inferred ownership.\n\nPersisted hierarchy:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session\n    capture turns\n      transcript records\n```\n\nStorage shape:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n```\n\nCore rules:\n\n- A capture turn is created only when capture accepts at least one new\n  transcript record.\n- `TurnDetail.records` is an ordered array and is authoritative for rendering\n  order within the capture turn.\n- Backfilled capture turns may contain many logical conversation/provider turns,\n  so records must carry provider/display grouping metadata when available.\n- `turn_key` is `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`, computed from UTF-8 stored\n  `session_key`, `s\n[TRUNCATED]\nering records within a capture turn; hashes and source indexes identify the\nrecords, but they are not a replacement for sequence.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part of capture turn identity. It exists to make\ninterval evidence cheap to evaluate, for example \"worktree files seen in the\nprevious turn later appeared in commits visible in this turn.\" The first capture\nturn omits the field.\n\nImplementation should write transcript records, record hashes, the capture turn\nobject, the turn summary list entry, and derived index entries as one logical\nGitMeta update.\nIf transcript record writes can succeed while the turn write fails, a later\nretry may see zero new records and skip the missing turn.\n\nCapture should also have a simple concurrency rule. Either hold a repo/session\ncapture lock around dedupe, previous-turn lookup, and write, or use optimistic\nretry if the record-hash set or latest turn summary changes before the atomic\nwrite. `previous_turn_key` means \"the latest committed capture turn in this\nsession immediately before this turn was written.\"\n\nIf an environment snapshot is written as `partial` or `failed`, a later retry may\nenrich that existing turn instead of creating a transcriptless turn. The\nenrichment must only update environment data and derived index entries for the\nsame capture turn, and should use the same atomic `apply_edits` path.\n\nGitMeta now has the needed atomic mixed-edit support. PR\n[`git-meta/git-meta#83`](https://github.com/git-meta/git-meta/pull/83) added\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:14:21.849Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}